%S A397708 1,1,6,26,200,1586,14732,141981,1429360,14729350,154785918
%N A397708 Number of face-connected components of n polyhedral cells in the sphenoid hendecahedral honeycomb, up to translation, rotation, and reflection of the honeycomb.
%C A397708 These are "free polyforms": counted up to all symmetries of the honeycomb.
%C A397708 The sphenoid hendecahedron is one of the five space-filling polyhedra described by Inchbald (1996). Its face-to-face honeycomb is unique: of the 4096 assignments of one gluing isometry per face, exactly one extends to a periodic tiling. The honeycomb is cell-transitive with 12 cells per translation-fundamental domain (two 6-cell "florets" on a hexagonal lattice) and a point group of order 24.
%D A397708 G. Inchbald, Five space-filling polyhedra, Math. Gaz. 80 (1996), 466-475.
%H A397708 Guy Inchbald, <a href="https://www.steelpillow.com/polyhedra/five_sf/five.html">Five Space-Filling Polyhedra</a>, updated version of the 1996 Math. Gaz. article.
%e A397708 For n = 2, two cells can share any of the 11 faces, but under the symmetries of the honeycomb these give only a(2) = 6 distinct compounds, one for each orbit of faces of the cell (three kite pairs, two triangle pairs, and the rhombus).
%Y A397708 Cf. A385028 (bisymmetric hendecahedral honeycomb), A038119 (cubic honeycomb).
